+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01M33rF81ngLXA2d1WfKcC4o","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RYcWJgejcPgQ7cJria42xh","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"gemini -p \"You are implementing a TypeScript solution for a factory reset puzzle. The project uses vitest for testing, TypeScript with ES2022/Node16 modules, and has package.json and tsconfig.json already set up. There is NO src/ directory yet — you need to create it.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### File: src/index.ts\n\nExport two functions:\n\n1. \\`solveToggle(machine: Machine): number[] | null\\`\n   - Machine has \\`target: boolean[]\\` and \\`buttons: number[][]\\`\n   - All lights start off (false). Each button toggles specific lights. Each button pressed at most once.\n   - Return sorted button indices to press to match target. Minimize presses, then lexicographically smallest.\n   - Return null if no solution. Must handle up to 40 buttons and 40 lights in <5s. Use GF(2) Gaussian elimination.\n\n2. \\`solveCounter(lights: number[], buttons: number[][], modulus: number): number[] | null\\`\n   - Counters start at 0. Buttons increment specific counters. Counters wrap at modulus (always prime).\n   - Each button pressed 0 to modulus-1 times.\n   - Return array where result[i] = presses for button i. Minimize total presses, then lexicographically smallest.\n   - Return null if no solution. Up to 40 buttons, 40 counters, modulus up to 97. Use GF(p) Gaussian elimination.\n\n3. Export the Machine interface: \\`interface Machine { target: boolean[]; buttons: number[][]; }\\`\n\n### Algorithm Details\n\nFor solveToggle: Model as a system of linear equations over GF(2). Build an augmented matrix where each column is a button (which lights it toggles), and the target is the augmented column. Do Gaussian elimination over GF(2). If inconsistent, return null. For free variables, enumerate all 2^k combinations (k = number of free variables, which will be small enough) to find the solution with fewest presses, then lexicographically smallest.\n\nFor solveCounter: Same approach but over GF(p) where p = modulus. Use modular arithmetic. For free variables, enumerate all p^k combinations to find minimum total presses, then lexicographically smallest.\n\n### Tests: src/index.test.ts\n\nWrite comprehensive tests using vitest covering:\n- The example from the spec (4 lights, 3 buttons, target [true,true,false,true] -> null)\n- Simple solvable cases\n- All lights already match target (empty solution)\n- Single button solutions\n- Multiple solutions choosing minimum presses\n- Lexicographic tiebreaking\n- No solution cases\n- Larger cases (10+ buttons/lights)\n- Counter puzzle: basic cases, modular arithmetic, no solution, prime modulus, lexicographic ordering\n- Edge cases: empty target, single light/button\n\nRun \\`npm install\\` first, then implement, then run \\`npm test\\`. Fix any failures. Don't stop until tests pass. Also run \\`npm run build\\` and \\`npm run lint\\` and fix issues.\" -y 2>&1","description":"Dispatch to Gemini to implement the solution","timeout":300000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":144,"cache_read_input_tokens":19427,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":144},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"12f97640-56f9-4480-af73-3031007ae613","uuid":"9f1f8bcc-f79d-4e5c-99bd-edeab22e69a1"}
